{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.21,0.32,0.05,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79198"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11044"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64550"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79198"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old male presented with fatigue and joint pain to his General Practitioner. Blood investigations were performed - thyroid function, infectious screening, renal function, HbA1C, iron studies and Tissue Transglutaminase IgA tests were performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a biochemical issue that can lead to osteoarthritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemochromatosis","Articular incongruity","Obesity","Joint hypermobility","Gout"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder that leads to excessive iron accumulation in the body, including the joints. This iron deposition can cause joint damage and lead to secondary osteoarthritis. An elevated serum ferritin and transferrin saturation would be expected suggesting iron overload, consistent with haemochromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArticular incongruity\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the misalignment or uneven surfaces of joint structures, which is a mechanical issue rather than a biochemical one. It can contribute to osteoarthritis by causing abnormal joint stress and wear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for osteoarthritis due to increased mechanical load on weight-bearing joints, but is not a biochemical issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint hypermobility\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to osteoarthritis due to increased joint laxity and instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition caused by the deposition of uric acid crystals in the joints, leading to inflammation and pain. While it can cause joint damage, it is a distinct condition from osteoarthritis and not a biochemical cause of it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemochromatosis can lead to secondary osteoarthritis due to iron deposition in joints.","Articular incongruity is a mechanical issue, not a biochemical one, contributing to osteoarthritis."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64550"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64550"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T17:15:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T17:16:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11044"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79198"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a